# Learnings — Loom-scoped, append-only.
# Contract: protocols/learnings.schema.toon
# Consumers: /loom-retro, /loom-learn, plan-*-review preambles.
schemaVersion: 1
learnings[7]{id,key,description,confidence,sourcePlan,sourceDate,domain,tags}:
  L-001,commands-are-audit-surface,"Loom commands are the audit-trail-generating layer. Direct file edits to Loom artifacts (ROADMAP, PLAN, contracts, notes) bypass changelog, wiki, and state-invalidation side effects. Rule: never edit a Loom artifact directly; always go through the corresponding Loom command. When you must edit directly (recovery, emergency), manually replicate the command's side effects.",9,gstack-adoption,2026-07-01,architecture,"audit-trail,principle"
  L-002,argument-surface-consistency,"Loom commands have inconsistent argument surfaces — --name is supported in some commands (roadmap:review, roadmap:converge) but not others (roadmap:mutate). --priority accepts only 'high' in mutate but arbitrary values in other places. Systemic issue that will keep surfacing UX gaps. Fix strategy: audit all commands, establish canonical flag conventions, ship author-time lint.",9,gstack-adoption,2026-07-01,ux,"consistency,flags,systemic"
  L-003,dogfood-surfaces-gaps-fast,"A 10-minute dogfood run of a new skill on itself surfaced 5 real backlog items (notes 037-041). Higher signal density than any structural review. Adopt as habit: before merging a new skill, dogfood once on a real task and note every friction point immediately.",8,gstack-adoption,2026-07-01,process,"dogfood,habit,capture"
  L-004,user-intent-over-directive-literal,"User's 'i dont care about the eval stuff' meant 'skip criteria-planner TDD scaffolding' — I read it as 'skip all quality gates' and cascaded into skipping plan-review + verify + convergence. Loss of quality signal. When operator gives scope-limiting directive, verify scope with specific example before cascading to strategic decisions like C-NN constraints.",8,gstack-adoption,2026-07-01,collaboration,"scope,cascade,misread"
  L-005,main-loop-serial-dispatch-workaround,"When /loom-auto trampoline hits sub-agent recursion limits in constrained runtimes, dispatching one implementer per phase directly from the main loop works cleanly. Not a substitute for trampoline (loses parallelism, wiring, verification gates) but adequate for shipping prose-heavy skills where implementers write independent files. Track via pipeline-state.toon.executionMode='main-loop-serial-implementers'.",8,gstack-adoption,2026-07-01,execution,"trampoline,fallback,runtime"
  L-006,live-skill-activation,"Skills symlinked to ~/.claude/skills/{name}/SKILL.md activate live in the current session — no restart required (contrary to documented /loom-library use post-install notice). Claude Code re-scans skills dynamically. Makes worktree-based dogfooding immediate: symlink once, iterate without session churn. Caveat: script paths in skill bodies are cwd-relative; resolve only when session runs from worktree that owns scripts.",7,gstack-adoption,2026-07-01,tooling,"skills,activation,symlink"
  L-007,synthesis-default-for-interview-skills,"Interview-shaped skills (/loom-think, /loom-spec, /loom-cso, /loom-retro) default to Socratic mode: skill body says 'operator writes answers.' Users often want synthesis mode instead: 'you produce the artifact from what I already told you.' Add synthesis as default with interview as opt-in via --interview flag. Detect fragmented single-word answers as signal to switch modes.",7,gstack-adoption,2026-07-01,skill-design,"interview,synthesis,default"
